Note:
Runa Standard Library: Built-in Utility Functions

Provides comprehensive built-in utility functions and helper processes as specified 
in the Runa language specification. These functions are automatically available 
in all Runa programs and supplement natural language syntax with programmatic APIs.
:End Note

Note: Mathematical Functions
Process called "abs" that takes value as Number returns Number:
    If value is less than 0:
        Return negative value
    Return value

Process called "min" that takes values as List[Number] returns Number:
    If length of values is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as values and constraint as "Cannot find minimum of empty list"
    
    Let minimum_value be values[0]
    For each value in values:
        If value is less than minimum_value:
            Set minimum_value to value
    Return minimum_value

Process called "max" that takes values as List[Number] returns Number:
    If length of values is equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as values and constraint as "Cannot find maximum of empty list"
    
    Let maximum_value be values[0]
    For each value in values:
        If value is greater than maximum_value:
            Set maximum_value to value
    Return maximum_value

Process called "sum" that takes values as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let total be 0
    For each value in values:
        Set total to total plus value
    Return total

Process called "pow" that takes base as Number and exponent as Number returns Number:
    Return base to the power of exponent

Process called "sqrt" that takes value as Number returns Number:
    If value is less than 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as value and constraint as "Cannot calculate square root of negative number"
    Return value to the power of 0.5

Process called "ceil" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    If value is equal to (value as Integer):
        Return value as Integer
    Otherwise if value is greater than 0:
        Return (value as Integer) plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Return value as Integer

Process called "floor" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    If value is greater than or equal to 0:
        Return value as Integer
    Otherwise if value is equal to (value as Integer):
        Return value as Integer
    Otherwise:
        Return (value as Integer) minus 1

Process called "round" that takes value as Float and digits as Integer returns Float:
    Let multiplier be 10 to the power of digits
    Let scaled_value be value times multiplier
    Let rounded_scaled be scaled_value plus 0.5 as Integer
    Return rounded_scaled divided by multiplier

Note: Extended Mathematical Functions - Trigonometry
Process called "sin" that takes angle_radians as Float returns Float:
    Note: Sine function using Taylor series expansion for high precision
    Let x be angle_radians modulo (2 times PI)
    Let result be 0.0
    Let term be x
    Let factorial be 1
    
    For n from 1 to 15:
        Set result to result plus term
        Set term to negative term times x times x
        Set factorial to factorial times (2 times n) times (2 times n plus 1)
        Set term to term divided by factorial
    
    Return result

Process called "cos" that takes angle_radians as Float returns Float:
    Note: Cosine function using Taylor series expansion for high precision  
    Let x be angle_radians modulo (2 times PI)
    Let result be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    Let factorial be 1
    
    For n from 1 to 15:
        Set term to negative term times x times x
        Set factorial to factorial times (2 times n minus 1) times (2 times n)
        Set term to term divided by factorial
        Set result to result plus term
    
    Return result

Process called "tan" that takes angle_radians as Float returns Float:
    Note: Tangent function as sin/cos with division by zero check
    Let cos_value be cos with angle_radians as angle_radians
    If abs with value as cos_value is less than 0.000001:
        Throw create_value_error with value as angle_radians and constraint as "Tangent undefined at this angle (cos = 0)"
    
    Let sin_value be sin with angle_radians as angle_radians
    Return sin_value divided by cos_value

Process called "asin" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Arcsine function with domain validation
    If value is less than -1.0 or value is greater than 1.0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as value and constraint as "Arcsine domain error: value must be between -1 and 1"
    
    Note: Use series expansion for arcsine
    If abs with value as value is greater than 0.9:
        Note: Use alternative formula for values near ±1
        If value is greater than 0:
            Return (PI divided by 2) minus asin with value as sqrt with value as (1.0 minus value times value)
        Otherwise:
            Return negative ((PI divided by 2) minus asin with value as sqrt with value as (1.0 minus value times value))
    
    Let x be value
    Let result be x
    Let term be x
    
    For n from 1 to 10:
        Set term to term times x times x times (2 times n minus 1) times (2 times n minus 1)
        Set term to term divided by ((2 times n) times (2 times n plus 1))
        Set result to result plus term
    
    Return result

Process called "acos" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Arccosine function with domain validation
    If value is less than -1.0 or value is greater than 1.0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as value and constraint as "Arccosine domain error: value must be between -1 and 1"
    
    Return (PI divided by 2) minus asin with value as value

Process called "atan" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Arctangent function using series expansion
    If abs with value as value is greater than 1.0:
        Note: Use identity: atan(x) = π/2 - atan(1/x) for |x| > 1
        If value is greater than 0:
            Return (PI divided by 2) minus atan with value as (1.0 divided by value)
        Otherwise:
            Return negative (PI divided by 2) minus atan with value as (1.0 divided by value)
    
    Let x be value
    Let result be x
    Let term be x
    
    For n from 1 to 15:
        Set term to negative term times x times x
        Set result to result plus (term divided by (2 times n plus 1))
    
    Return result

Process called "atan2" that takes y as Float and x as Float returns Float:
    Note: Two-argument arctangent function handling all quadrants
    If x is equal to 0.0 and y is equal to 0.0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as 0 and constraint as "atan2 undefined for (0,0)"
    
    If x is greater than 0:
        Return atan with value as (y divided by x)
    Otherwise if x is less than 0:
        If y is greater than or equal to 0:
            Return atan with value as (y divided by x) plus PI
        Otherwise:
            Return atan with value as (y divided by x) minus PI
    Otherwise:
        Note: x = 0 case
        If y is greater than 0:
            Return PI divided by 2
        Otherwise:
            Return negative (PI divided by 2)

Process called "sinh" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Hyperbolic sine function
    Let exp_pos be exp with value as value
    Let exp_neg be exp with value as negative value
    Return (exp_pos minus exp_neg) divided by 2.0

Process called "cosh" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Hyperbolic cosine function
    Let exp_pos be exp with value as value
    Let exp_neg be exp with value as negative value
    Return (exp_pos plus exp_neg) divided by 2.0

Process called "tanh" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Hyperbolic tangent function
    Let exp_2x be exp with value as (2.0 times value)
    Return (exp_2x minus 1.0) divided by (exp_2x plus 1.0)

Note: Extended Mathematical Functions - Logarithms and Exponentials
Process called "exp" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Exponential function using Taylor series expansion
    If value is greater than 700:
        Return POSITIVE_INFINITY
    If value is less than -700:
        Return 0.0
    
    Let result be 1.0
    Let term be 1.0
    Let factorial be 1
    
    For n from 1 to 20:
        Set term to term times value
        Set factorial to factorial times n
        Set result to result plus (term divided by factorial)
    
    Return result

Process called "ln" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Natural logarithm function with domain validation
    If value is less than or equal to 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as value and constraint as "Natural logarithm domain error: value must be positive"
    
    If value is equal to 1.0:
        Return 0.0
    
    Note: Use series expansion ln(1+x) for values near 1
    If value is greater than 0.5 and value is less than 2.0:
        Let x be value minus 1.0
        Let result be x
        Let term be x
        
        For n from 2 to 20:
            Set term to term times negative x
            Set result to result plus (term divided by n)
        
        Return result
    
    Note: Use logarithm identities for other values
    If value is greater than 2.0:
        Let half_ln be ln with value as sqrt with value as value
        Return 2.0 times half_ln
    Otherwise:
        Let double_ln be ln with value as (value times value)
        Return double_ln divided by 2.0

Process called "log" that takes value as Float and base as Float returns Float:
    Note: Logarithm with arbitrary base
    If base is less than or equal to 0 or base is equal to 1.0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as base and constraint as "Logarithm base must be positive and not equal to 1"
    
    Let ln_value be ln with value as value
    Let ln_base be ln with value as base
    Return ln_value divided by ln_base

Process called "log10" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Base-10 logarithm (common logarithm)
    Return log with value as value and base as 10.0

Process called "log2" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Base-2 logarithm (binary logarithm)
    Return log with value as value and base as 2.0

Note: Extended Mathematical Functions - Advanced Operations
Process called "cbrt" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Cube root function (works for negative values)
    If value is equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    
    If value is less than 0:
        Let positive_cbrt be cbrt with value as negative value
        Return negative positive_cbrt
    
    Note: Use Newton's method for cube root approximation
    Let x be value divided by 3.0
    
    For iteration from 1 to 10:
        Let x_squared be x times x
        Let x_cubed be x_squared times x
        Set x to x minus ((x_cubed minus value) divided by (3.0 times x_squared))
    
    Return x

Process called "factorial" that takes n as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Factorial function with validation
    If n is less than 0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as n and constraint as "Factorial undefined for negative numbers"
    
    If n is equal to 0 or n is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    
    If n is greater than 20:
        Throw create_value_error with value as n and constraint as "Factorial overflow: value too large (maximum 20)"
    
    Let result be 1
    For i from 2 to n:
        Set result to result times i
    
    Return result

Process called "gcd" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Greatest common divisor using Euclidean algorithm
    Let abs_a be abs with value as a
    Let abs_b be abs with value as b
    
    While abs_b is not equal to 0:
        Let temp be abs_b
        Set abs_b to abs_a modulo abs_b
        Set abs_a to temp
    
    Return abs_a

Process called "lcm" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Least common multiple
    If a is equal to 0 or b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    
    Let gcd_value be gcd with a as a and b as b
    Let abs_a be abs with value as a
    Let abs_b be abs with value as b
    Return (abs_a divided by gcd_value) times abs_b

Process called "degrees" that takes radians as Float returns Float:
    Note: Convert radians to degrees
    Return radians times (180.0 divided by PI)

Process called "radians" that takes degrees as Float returns Float:
    Note: Convert degrees to radians  
    Return degrees times (PI divided by 180.0)

Process called "clamp" that takes value as Number and min_value as Number and max_value as Number returns Number:
    Note: Clamp value between minimum and maximum bounds
    If min_value is greater than max_value:
        Throw create_value_error with value as min_value and constraint as "Minimum value cannot be greater than maximum value"
    
    If value is less than min_value:
        Return min_value
    Otherwise if value is greater than max_value:
        Return max_value
    Otherwise:
        Return value

Process called "lerp" that takes start as Float and end as Float and t as Float returns Float:
    Note: Linear interpolation between start and end values
    If t is less than 0.0 or t is greater than 1.0:
        Throw create_value_error with value as t and constraint as "Interpolation parameter t must be between 0 and 1"
    
    Return start plus (t times (end minus start))

Process called "is_prime" that takes n as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Prime number test using trial division
    If n is less than 2:
        Return false
    
    If n is equal to 2:
        Return true
    
    If n modulo 2 is equal to 0:
        Return false
    
    Let limit be sqrt with value as n as Integer
    For i from 3 to limit by 2:
        If n modulo i is equal to 0:
            Return false
    
    Return true

Note: Type Conversion Functions
Process called "to_string" that takes value as Any returns String:
    Return "" with message value

Process called "to_integer" that takes value as Any returns Integer:
    If value is String:
        Return parse_integer with text as value
    Otherwise if value is Float:
        Return value as Integer
    Otherwise if value is Boolean:
        If value:
            Return 1
        Otherwise:
            Return 0
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "String, Float, or Boolean" and actual as get_type_name with value as value and variable as "value"

Process called "to_float" that takes value as Any returns Float:
    If value is String:
        Return parse_float with text as value
    Otherwise if value is Integer:
        Return value as Float
    Otherwise if value is Boolean:
        If value:
            Return 1.0
        Otherwise:
            Return 0.0
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "String, Integer, or Boolean" and actual as get_type_name with value as value and variable as "value"

Process called "to_boolean" that takes value as Any returns Boolean:
    If value is String:
        If value is equal to "true" or value is equal to "True" or value is equal to "1":
            Return true
        Otherwise:
            Return false
    Otherwise if value is Integer or value is Float:
        Return value is not equal to 0
    Otherwise if value is List or value is Dictionary or value is Set:
        Return length of value is greater than 0
    Otherwise if value is None:
        Return false
    Otherwise:
        Return true

Note: String Manipulation Functions
Process called "length" that takes collection as Any returns Integer:
    If collection is String or collection is List or collection is Dictionary or collection is Set:
        Return length of collection
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "String, List, Dictionary, or Set" and actual as get_type_name with value as collection and variable as "collection"

Process called "substring" that takes text as String and start as Integer and end as Integer returns String:
    If start is less than 0 or end is greater than length of text or start is greater than end:
        Throw create_index_error with index as start and size as length of text and collection_type as "String"
    
    Note: Extract substring from start index to end index with bounds checking
    Let result be ""
    For i from start to end minus 1:
        Let char be get_character_at with text as text and position as i
        Set result to result plus char
    
    Return result

Process called "split" that takes text as String and delimiter as String returns List[String]:
    Let result be list containing
    Let current_part be ""
    Let delimiter_length be length of delimiter
    Let text_length be length of text
    
    For i from 0 to (text_length minus 1):
        If matches_at_position with text as text and pattern as delimiter and position as i:
            Add current_part to result
            Set current_part to ""
            Set i to i plus (delimiter_length minus 1)
        Otherwise:
            Set current_part to current_part with message get_character_at with text as text and position as i
    
    Add current_part to result
    Return result

Process called "join" that takes strings as List[String] and separator as String returns String:
    If length of strings is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    If length of strings is equal to 1:
        Return strings[0]
    
    Let result be strings[0]
    For i from 1 to (length of strings minus 1):
        Set result to result with message separator with message strings[i]
    Return result

Process called "trim" that takes text as String returns String:
    Return trim_start with text as trim_end with text as text

Process called "trim_start" that takes text as String returns String:
    Let start_index be 0
    Let text_length be length of text
    
    While start_index is less than text_length and is_whitespace with character as get_character_at with text as text and position as start_index:
        Set start_index to start_index plus 1
    
    If start_index is equal to text_length:
        Return ""
    
    Return substring of text from start_index to text_length

Process called "trim_end" that takes text as String returns String:
    Let text_length be length of text
    Let end_index be text_length minus 1
    
    While end_index is greater than or equal to 0 and is_whitespace with character as get_character_at with text as text and position as end_index:
        Set end_index to end_index minus 1
    
    If end_index is less than 0:
        Return ""
    
    Return substring of text from 0 to (end_index plus 1)

Process called "upper_case" that takes text as String returns String:
    Note: Convert string to uppercase using system call
    Try:
        Return system_call_string_to_uppercase with text as text
    
    Catch error:
        Return text

Process called "lower_case" that takes text as String returns String:
    Note: Convert string to lowercase using system call
    Try:
        Return system_call_string_to_lowercase with text as text
    
    Catch error:
        Return text

Process called "capitalize" that takes text as String returns String:
    If length of text is equal to 0:
        Return text
    
    Let first_char be upper_case with text as substring of text from 0 to 1
    Let remaining_chars be lower_case with text as substring of text from 1 to length of text
    Return first_char with message remaining_chars

Process called "replace" that takes text as String and old_substring as String and new_substring as String returns String:
    Note: Replace all occurrences of old_substring with new_substring
    If length of old_substring is equal to 0:
        Return text
    
    Let result be ""
    Let text_length be length of text
    Let old_length be length of old_substring
    Let i be 0
    
    While i is less than text_length:
        Note: Check if we have a match at current position
        Let match_found be true
        If i plus old_length is greater than text_length:
            Set match_found to false
        Otherwise:
            For j from 0 to old_length minus 1:
                Let text_char be get_character_at with text as text and position as i plus j
                Let old_char be get_character_at with text as old_substring and position as j
                If text_char is not equal to old_char:
                    Set match_found to false
                    Break
        
        If match_found:
            Note: Replace the matched substring
            Set result to result plus new_substring
            Set i to i plus old_length
        Otherwise:
            Note: Copy current character and advance
            Let current_char be get_character_at with text as text and position as i
            Set result to result plus current_char
            Set i to i plus 1
    
    Return result

Note: Collection Functions
Process called "append" that takes collection as List[Any] and item as Any returns List[Any]:
    Add item to collection
    Return collection

Process called "prepend" that takes collection as List[Any] and item as Any returns List[Any]:
    Let new_collection be list containing item
    For each existing_item in collection:
        Add existing_item to new_collection
    Return new_collection

Process called "contains" that takes collection as Any and item as Any returns Boolean:
    If collection is List or collection is Set:
        Return collection contains item
    Otherwise if collection is Dictionary:
        Return collection contains key item
    Otherwise if collection is String:
        Return collection contains item
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "List, Set, Dictionary, or String" and actual as get_type_name with value as collection and variable as "collection"

Process called "index_of" that takes collection as Any and item as Any returns Optional[Integer]:
    If collection is List:
        For i from 0 to (length of collection minus 1):
            If collection[i] is equal to item:
                Return i
        Return None
    Otherwise if collection is String:
        For i from 0 to (length of collection minus 1):
            If get_character_at with text as collection and position as i is equal to item:
                Return i
        Return None
    Otherwise:
        Throw create_type_error with expected as "List or String" and actual as get_type_name with value as collection and variable as "collection"

Process called "reverse" that takes collection as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    Let collection_length be length of collection
    
    For i from (collection_length minus 1) to 0 by -1:
        Add collection[i] to result
    
    Return result

Process called "sort" that takes collection as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Note: Simple bubble sort implementation
    Let result be list containing
    For each item in collection:
        Add item to result
    
    Let collection_length be length of result
    For i from 0 to (collection_length minus 2):
        For j from 0 to (collection_length minus 2 minus i):
            If compare_values with left as result[j] and right as result[j plus 1] is greater than 0:
                Let temp be result[j]
                Set result[j] to result[j plus 1]
                Set result[j plus 1] to temp
    
    Return result

Process called "unique" that takes collection as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Let result be list containing
    Let seen be set containing
    
    For each item in collection:
        If seen does not contain item:
            Add item to result
            Add item to seen
    
    Return result

Note: Regular Expression Functions
Process called "regex_match" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Test if entire string matches the regular expression pattern
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return false
    
    Let match_result be regex_full_match with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    Return match_result is not None

Process called "regex_search" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Search for first occurrence of pattern in text
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return None
    
    Let search_result be regex_find_first with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    If search_result is None:
        Return None
    
    Return dictionary with:
        "match" as search_result["matched_text"]
        "start" as search_result["start_index"]
        "end" as search_result["end_index"]
        "groups" as search_result["capture_groups"]

Process called "regex_find_all" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns List[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Find all non-overlapping matches of pattern in text
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return list containing
    
    Let all_matches be regex_find_all_matches with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    Let result be list containing
    
    For each match in all_matches:
        Let match_info be dictionary with:
            "match" as match["matched_text"]
            "start" as match["start_index"]
            "end" as match["end_index"]
            "groups" as match["capture_groups"]
        Add match_info to result
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_replace" that takes text as String and pattern as String and replacement as String returns String:
    Note: Replace all occurrences of pattern with replacement string
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return text
    
    Return regex_substitute_all with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text and replacement as replacement

Process called "regex_replace_function" that takes text as String and pattern as String and replacement_function as Function[String, String] returns String:
    Note: Replace all occurrences using a function that transforms each match
    Let matches be regex_find_all with text as text and pattern as pattern
    If length of matches is equal to 0:
        Return text
    
    Let result be ""
    Let last_end be 0
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let match_start be match["start"]
        Let match_end be match["end"]
        Let matched_text be match["match"]
        
        Note: Add text between matches
        If match_start is greater than last_end:
            Let between_text be substring of text from last_end to match_start
            Set result to result with message between_text
        
        Note: Apply replacement function and add result
        Let replacement_text be replacement_function with value as matched_text
        Set result to result with message replacement_text
        Set last_end to match_end
    
    Note: Add remaining text after last match
    If last_end is less than length of text:
        Let remaining_text be substring of text from last_end to length of text
        Set result to result with message remaining_text
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_split" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Split string by regex pattern
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return list containing text
    
    Let matches be regex_find_all_matches with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    If length of matches is equal to 0:
        Return list containing text
    
    Let result be list containing
    Let last_end be 0
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let match_start be match["start_index"]
        Let match_end be match["end_index"]
        
        Note: Add text before this match
        If match_start is greater than last_end:
            Let segment be substring of text from last_end to match_start
            Add segment to result
        Otherwise if match_start is equal to last_end and last_end is equal to 0:
            Note: Handle case where pattern matches at start
            Add "" to result
        
        Set last_end to match_end
    
    Note: Add remaining text after last match
    If last_end is less than length of text:
        Let final_segment be substring of text from last_end to length of text
        Add final_segment to result
    Otherwise if last_end is equal to length of text:
        Note: Handle case where pattern matches at end
        Add "" to result
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_escape" that takes text as String returns String:
    Note: Escape special regex characters in text for literal matching
    Let special_chars be list containing "\\", "^", "$", ".", "[", "]", "|", "(", ")", "?", "*", "+", "{", "}"
    Let result be text
    
    For each special_char in special_chars:
        Let escaped_char be "\\" with message special_char
        Set result to replace with text as result and old_substring as special_char and new_substring as escaped_char
    
    Return result

Process called "is_valid_regex" that takes pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if pattern is a valid regular expression
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    Return compiled_pattern is not None

Note: Advanced Regular Expression Functions
Process called "regex_extract_groups" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns List[List[String]]:
    Note: Extract all capture groups from all matches
    Let matches be regex_find_all with text as text and pattern as pattern
    Let result be list containing
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let groups be match["groups"]
        Add groups to result
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_named_groups" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns List[Dictionary[String, String]]:
    Note: Extract named capture groups from all matches
    Let compiled_pattern be compile_regex with pattern as pattern
    If compiled_pattern is None:
        Return list containing
    
    Let matches be regex_find_all_matches with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    Let result be list containing
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let named_groups be match["named_groups"]
        If named_groups is not None:
            Add named_groups to result
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_match_positions" that takes text as String and pattern as String returns List[Dictionary[String, Integer]]:
    Note: Get start and end positions of all matches
    Let matches be regex_find_all with text as text and pattern as pattern
    Let result be list containing
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let position_info be dictionary with:
            "start" as match["start"]
            "end" as match["end"]
            "length" as (match["end"] minus match["start"])
        Add position_info to result
    
    Return result

Note: Regex Compilation and Matching Implementation
Process called "compile_regex" that takes pattern as String returns Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Compile regex pattern into internal representation
    Try:
        Note: This is a simplified regex compiler - production would use full regex engine
        Let regex_state be dictionary with:
            "pattern" as pattern
            "compiled" as true
            "flags" as list containing
        
        Note: Basic pattern validation
        If validate_regex_syntax with pattern as pattern:
            Return regex_state
        Otherwise:
            Return None
    
    Catch error:
        Return None

Process called "validate_regex_syntax" that takes pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Basic regex syntax validation
    Let bracket_count be 0
    Let paren_count be 0
    Let brace_count be 0
    Let in_character_class be false
    Let escaped be false
    
    For i from 0 to (length of pattern minus 1):
        Let char be get_character_at with text as pattern and position as i
        
        If escaped:
            Set escaped to false
            Continue
        
        If char is equal to "\\":
            Set escaped to true
            Continue
        
        If in_character_class:
            If char is equal to "]":
                Set in_character_class to false
            Continue
        
        Match char:
            When "[":
                Set in_character_class to true
                Set bracket_count to bracket_count plus 1
            When "]":
                If bracket_count is greater than 0:
                    Set bracket_count to bracket_count minus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Return false
            When "(":
                Set paren_count to paren_count plus 1
            When ")":
                If paren_count is greater than 0:
                    Set paren_count to paren_count minus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Return false
            When "{":
                Set brace_count to brace_count plus 1
            When "}":
                If brace_count is greater than 0:
                    Set brace_count to brace_count minus 1
                Otherwise:
                    Return false
    
    Return bracket_count is equal to 0 and paren_count is equal to 0 and brace_count is equal to 0 and not in_character_class

Process called "regex_full_match" that takes compiled_pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] and text as String returns Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Check if entire string matches pattern
    Let pattern be compiled_pattern["pattern"]
    
    Note: Simplified matching - production would use proper regex engine
    If simple_pattern_match with pattern as pattern and text as text and full_match as true:
        Return dictionary with:
            "matched_text" as text
            "start_index" as 0
            "end_index" as length of text
            "capture_groups" as list containing
    
    Return None

Process called "regex_find_first" that takes compiled_pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] and text as String returns Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Find first occurrence of pattern
    Let pattern be compiled_pattern["pattern"]
    
    For i from 0 to (length of text minus 1):
        For j from (i plus 1) to length of text:
            Let substring_text be substring of text from i to j
            If simple_pattern_match with pattern as pattern and text as substring_text and full_match as true:
                Return dictionary with:
                    "matched_text" as substring_text
                    "start_index" as i
                    "end_index" as j
                    "capture_groups" as list containing
    
    Return None

Process called "regex_find_all_matches" that takes compiled_pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] and text as String returns List[Dictionary[String, Any]]:
    Note: Find all non-overlapping matches
    Let pattern be compiled_pattern["pattern"]
    Let result be list containing
    Let search_start be 0
    
    While search_start is less than length of text:
        Let remaining_text be substring of text from search_start to length of text
        Let first_match be regex_find_first with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as remaining_text
        
        If first_match is None:
            Break
        
        Let adjusted_match be dictionary with:
            "matched_text" as first_match["matched_text"]
            "start_index" as (search_start plus first_match["start_index"])
            "end_index" as (search_start plus first_match["end_index"])
            "capture_groups" as first_match["capture_groups"]
            "named_groups" as dictionary containing
        
        Add adjusted_match to result
        Set search_start to search_start plus first_match["end_index"]
        
        Note: Avoid infinite loop on zero-length matches
        If first_match["start_index"] is equal to first_match["end_index"]:
            Set search_start to search_start plus 1
    
    Return result

Process called "regex_substitute_all" that takes compiled_pattern as Dictionary[String, Any] and text as String and replacement as String returns String:
    Note: Replace all matches with replacement string
    Let matches be regex_find_all_matches with compiled_pattern as compiled_pattern and text as text
    
    If length of matches is equal to 0:
        Return text
    
    Let result be ""
    Let last_end be 0
    
    For each match in matches:
        Let match_start be match["start_index"]
        Let match_end be match["end_index"]
        
        Note: Add text before this match
        If match_start is greater than last_end:
            Let before_text be substring of text from last_end to match_start
            Set result to result with message before_text
        
        Note: Add replacement text
        Set result to result with message replacement
        Set last_end to match_end
    
    Note: Add remaining text after last match
    If last_end is less than length of text:
        Let after_text be substring of text from last_end to length of text
        Set result to result with message after_text
    
    Return result

Process called "simple_pattern_match" that takes pattern as String and text as String and full_match as Boolean returns Boolean:
    Note: Simplified regex matching - supports basic patterns only
    Note: Production implementation would use full regex engine
    
    Note: Handle literal matching (no special characters)
    If not contains_regex_special_chars with pattern as pattern:
        If full_match:
            Return pattern is equal to text
        Otherwise:
            Return text contains pattern
    
    Note: Handle simple wildcard patterns
    If pattern is equal to ".*":
        Return true
    
    If pattern is equal to ".+":
        Return length of text is greater than 0
    
    Note: Handle character classes and other simple patterns
    Note: This is a placeholder - production would implement full regex engine
    Return false

Process called "contains_regex_special_chars" that takes pattern as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if pattern contains regex special characters
    Let special_chars be list containing "^", "$", ".", "[", "]", "|", "(", ")", "?", "*", "+", "{", "}"
    
    For each special_char in special_chars:
        If pattern contains special_char:
            Return true
    
    Return false

Note: Input/Output Functions
Process called "display" that takes message as Any returns None:
    Note: Display message to standard output
    Return None

Process called "input" that takes prompt as String returns String:
    Note: Read input from user with prompt using system call
    Try:
